      "content": "Critics label substantive due process \"judicial activism\" because they argue that unelected judges are imposing their own personal policy preferences onto the Constitution rather than simply interpreting the text. They claim the amendment doesn't explicitly list these modern rights, meaning judges are inventing rights rather than discovering them. This viewpoint fundamentally rejects the idea that the judiciary should be the primary driver of social change, preferring that elected legislatures handle those issues. Therefore, the controversy stems from a deep disagreement over the proper role of the courts versus the will of the people.",
